<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478"><gtr:id>C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Institute of Hearing Research</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478"><gtr:id>C4145C68-58B8-441E-86DD-A4079B65B478</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC Institute of Hearing Research</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Park</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Nottingham</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>NG7 2RD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East Midlands</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/39DDCB99-3651-4B2D-9450-175D10C5DEDD"><gtr:id>39DDCB99-3651-4B2D-9450-175D10C5DEDD</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Michael</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Akeroyd</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0002-7182-9209</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U135079244"><gtr:id>0FC9E9FC-DC1F-4F9C-9D56-1350997BC207</gtr:id><gtr:title>The auditory brain, hearing disability and handicap in adults</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U135079244</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Hearing disability is often characterised simply in terms of reduced speech intelligibility. But &amp;quot;active&amp;quot; listening in the everyday world, as opposed to passive hearing, involves abilities to deal with the rapidly changing patterns in space and time of objects that in turn depend upon cognitive or attentional capacities. This is especially relevant for hearing-impaired listeners, who suffer deficits in complex environments and have to rely to an increasing extent on attentional and cognitive abilities to overcome the consequences of impaired hearing. Our goal is to study how hearing-impaired listeners perform in realistic environments and how that relates to attentional and cognitive skills.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Assessment of the disabling consequences of impaired hearing is usually restricted to measures and reports of speech intelligibility in static and constrained laboratory circumstances. But the consequences of impaired hearing appear in more than just simple tests of speech-in-noise: they also speech understanding in complex situations with multiple background sounds, in sustaining and switching attention, in dynamic aspects of spatial hearing and the appreciation of distance and movement, in sound quality and naturalness, segregation of sounds, and in the effort needed for listening. The goal of this work is to collect data from clinical and population samples and to ascertain the extent to which the different dimensions of disability impact upon and lead to the experience of hearing handicap.

To date we have used the IHR Speaker Ring to generate assessments of auditory spatial attention and the appreciation of the distance of acoustic objects. The former has shown significant influences of generalised (i.e. not specifically auditory) attentional capacities on all components of auditory disability, though only influences of specifically auditory attentional capacities affecton speech understanding in complex dynamic listening circumstances. The latter has shown that hearing-impaired listeners can have difficulties in some aspects of distance perception. We have also demonstrated that informational masking for speech is no worse in hearing-impaired adults (a somewhat surprising result) and so is unlikely to be an additional source of difficulites in understanding speech in complex situations 

We have also prepared a major survey of how cognitive skills link to speech perception, covering 20 studies published over the last 20 years. This has informed a new series of experiments looking at cognitive predictors of speech reception in dynamically-changing noises.

Note that this programme has been replaced from 2009/10 onwards by the programme &amp;quot;Auditory disability and spatial hearing&amp;quot;. See www.ihr.mrc.ac.uk/research2009/index.php?page=8 for details.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>287040</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>I developed a &amp;quot;Matlab&amp;quot; toolbox for running computational models of binaural (spatial) hearing. In recent years the software has been extended and parts have been supplied to occasional other researchers on request.</gtr:description><gtr:id>E5DAC0E0-8A99-4FE9-974E-4FB9636B5D4C</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The software has proved extremely useful to me and is at the heart of all our current experimental and model systems (800+ programs)</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>6E0602803C8</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>2006 - Binaural toolbox for Matlab</gtr:title><gtr:type>Improvements to research infrastructure</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2006</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A8C011B0-467D-48A0-8D05-FBFE4DC0F158</gtr:id><gtr:title>The detection of differences in the cues to distance by elderly h